<br>
I've been playing the game since long before Ascent was a guild.  They were simply used as an example of a guild that can mobilize quickly.  To say that once the really fast mobilizing guilds are gone, the others are irrelevant is just not true.  They easily COULD have raced each other to RF in solB.  Sure they wouldn't outrace AoD or DA or whoever if those guilds had been there, but they'd have a shot at outracing each other.  They chose not to.  I understand Jeet's argument and I find it flawed.  That's my opinion.  But don't tell someone who's been playing the game well over 2 years that they lack the perspective/experience just because you might have been there since Beta or whatever.  Who cares.<br>
<br>
&quot;There is alot of grey. How much, in this case, seems to be based on whether you are either pro-list or anti-list, for the &quot;rules&quot; or think they need changing etc.&quot;<br>
<br>
Actually I think the list has gotten silly, but I also think the way EiE has chosen to deal with it is wrong.<br>
<br>
&quot;Anything that is not FFA is never going to be anything more than a gentleman's agreement to begin with.&quot;<br>
<br>
Correct.<br>
<br>
&quot;According to the &quot;rules&quot; that are in place Melissa did not break any of them. THEN you wanna<br>
talk about the spirit versus the letter of the law, and doing what is &quot;right&quot; or &quot;fair&quot;.  So just following the rules is not enough. Then why do you have them? Hell, follow the rules and you get flamed on a board like this. Apparently doing what was right was not good enough for someone because they felt the need to start this &quot;list&quot; and make these &quot;rules&quot;.&quot;<br>
<br>
I've said from the beginning that no Verant rules were broken.  But yes, I'm arguing for what's &quot;right&quot; or &quot;fair&quot; if you want to put it that way.  Rules/laws seldom cover everything and people still have a lot of choice about whether to treat each other with respect or to not do so without violating any rules/laws.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Now it has to be both ways. Looks more to me like someone's friend got their feelings hurt and so they came here to do some name calling to make themselves feel better over it.&quot;<br>
<br>
Actually I don't know the cleric who was camping it at all.<br>
<br>
&quot;Then a lot of people jump on the &quot;anti-uber&quot; band wagon based on heresay and we are left with what we have here. Leave your spite and jealousy behind and look at the facts. You will see a lot different picture than the one you are painting.&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm on the &quot;anti-uber&quot; bandwagon because of how I see so many of them treat other players.  It's not ALL people in the so called uber guilds, not by any means.  Jealous?  No, I could have aimed at joining a top tier guild.  I chose not to.  What I see are people who play the game far more competitively than most of the player populace does.  There are some, again not all, in these guilds who could care less about someone else's time and effort.  If they can take what they want through superior force, they will do it regardless of who might be pushed aside in the process.  <br>
<br>
---------------<br>
<br>
&quot;And why the adverb &quot;simply&quot;? Rules are rules; attempting to trivialize them does not change that. No player in the game is above the rules, and has the right to expect more than what the rules entitle them to receive.&quot;<br>
<br>
It's nice to think that people will be kind to one another without rules/laws forcing them to do so.  Sorry if that's naive.<br>
<br>
I think the main difference we're getting at is that for something in a game like camping that silly ragefire spawn, you see giving the person who's been camping it all week first shot as doing them a favor.  You're giving them a handout... a random act of kindness.  It's not something they should expect.  I see it as no huge favor at all, but simple respect for their time and effort that should be given to everyone and is something we should expect from one another.<br>
<br>
&quot;Why, because we aren't as charitable to non-ubers as you would like us to be?&quot;<br>
<br>
I don't see choosing NOT to trample their time and effort with superior power as an act of charity but of simple respect.  The fact that you see it as some big favor you're doing for the little guy says something about the uber guild mentality, once again of some top tier guild players, not all, and why the anti bandwagon exists.  <br>
<br>
-- Callon <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub59.ezboard.com/ueldryc.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Eldryc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Cons Threateningly </span><br>  Posts: 74<br> <font color=#333333>(7/24/02 12:52:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub59.ezboard.com/fguild75784frm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=92.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Response to the now locked RF thread</span><hr size=1> Bah, there's no edit button for my post... was gonna change the subject at the least.  And yes, I'm most likely beating a dead horse with this crap.  Maybe I'm just bored.<br>
